Lifetime (Expiration)
Local Storage: Data is persistent. It stays in the browser even if you close the tab, close the window, or restart your computer. It only disappears if you manually delete it or clear your browser cache.

Session Storage: Data is temporary. It only lasts as long as the specific browser tab is open. Once you close that tab, the data is wiped out.

2. Scope (Accessibility)
Local Storage: Shared across all tabs and windows from the same origin (the same website URL). If you save something in one tab, you can access it in another.

Session Storage: Restricted to the specific tab where it was created. Even if you open the same website in a new tab, it will have its own separate session storage.